{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781082370255,"sessionID":"ses_14f38057bffeIT5v3QDi2oCNBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_01E8aEixMPHv4ZMhXMDoVUq3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-quoting/instruction.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-quoting/instruction.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Rust `ls` — Quoting & Escaping\n2: \n3: ## Task\n4: \n5: Build an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n6: **name quoting and escaping**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary\n7: located at `/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n8: \n9: ```\n10: /app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n11: ```\n12: \n13: For the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\n14: output as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses entirely on **how filenames\n15: containing spaces, quotes, tabs, newlines, backslashes, and control characters\n16: are rendered** — long format, sorting, columns, color, and recursion are not the\n17: focus here (entries are still name-sorted).\n18: \n19: ## Required Flags\n20: \n21: You must support the following flags. Behavior must match GNU coreutils `ls`\n22: exactly.\n23: \n24: | Flag | Description |\n25: |------|-------------|\n26: | `-b`, `--escape` | Print C-style escapes (`\\t`, `\\n`, `\\\\`, `\\NNN`, …) for non-graphic chars |\n27: | `-q`, `--hide-control-chars` | Print `?` for each non-graphic char |\n28: | `-Q`, `--quote-name` | Enclose names in double quotes |\n29: | `-N`, `--literal` | Print raw names with no quoting or escaping |\n30: | `--show-control-chars` | Show non-graphic chars as-is (the opposite of `-q`) |\n31: | `--quoting-style=WORD` | `literal` / `shell` / `shell-always` / `shell-escape` / `shell-escape-always` / `c` / `escape` |\n32: \n33: ### Combined in some cases\n34: \n35: | Flag | Description |\n36: |------|-------------|\n37: | `-l` | Long listing (cases that use it require correct long output) |\n38: \n39: ## Environment Variables\n40: \n41: | Variable | Usage |\n42: |----------|-------|\n43: | `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order and which bytes count as printable |\n44: | `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n45: | `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n46: \n47: ## Output Behavior\n48: \n49: The default quoting style for GNU `ls` is **`shell-escape`** when output is not\n50: a terminal in recent coreutils — however, the test environment pins behavior via\n51: flags, so implement each named style precisely:\n52: \n53: - **`literal`** (`-N`): emit the raw bytes, no quoting.\n54: - **`shell`**: quote with single quotes only when needed (spaces, shell\n55:   metacharacters); otherwise bare.\n56: - **`shell-always`**: always single-quote.\n57: - **`shell-escape`** / **`shell-escape-always`**: like shell/shell-always but\n58:   use `$'…'` ANSI-C quoting for names containing control characters.\n59: - **`c`** (also `-Q`): double-quote the name and apply C escapes (`\\t`, `\\n`,\n60:   `\\\"`, `\\\\`, octal `\\NNN`).\n61: - **`escape`** (`-b`): C-style escapes **without** the surrounding quotes.\n62: - **`-q`** replaces every non-graphic character with `?` (independent of style).\n63: - **`--show-control-chars`** turns off the `-q` default substitution.\n64: \n65: When several of these are combined, GNU `ls` applies a defined precedence —\n66: reproduce it so the exact byte output matches.\n67: \n68: - **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n69: \n70: ## Evaluation\n71: \n72: Your implementation is evaluated against a hidden suite built on a fixture of\n73: filenames containing spaces, single/double quotes, tabs, backslashes, embedded\n74: control characters, and a newline, plus a few ordinary fixtures. Each case runs\n75: your binary and GNU `ls` on the same inputs, flags, and environment, and\n76: compares output after trailing-whitespace normalization on each line; they must\n77: match exactly.\n78: \n79: ## Time Limit\n80: \n81: You have **2 hours** (7200 seconds). Implement `literal` first, then the `c`/\n82: `escape` styles, then the `shell*` family, then the `-q` substitution. When ~10\n83: minutes remain, run a final `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to\n84: `/app/workspace/rls`, and make sure it runs without crashing.\n85: \n86: ## Constraints\n87: \n88: - You must implement this in **Rust**.\n89: - You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n90:   ready-made `ls` implementation.\n91: - You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n92:   `nix`, `clap`).\n93: - Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n94: - The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n95: - Each test has a per-case timeout (10 seconds).\n96: \n97: ## Getting Started\n98: \n99: Example fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n100: `/app/fixtures/` and test definitions in `/app/tests/`.\n101: \n102: ## Tips\n103: \n104: - Work at the **byte** level, not UTF-8 — filenames are arbitrary byte strings,\n105:   and under `LC_ALL=C` any byte outside the printable ASCII range (0x20–0x7E)\n106:   is \"non-graphic\" and subject to escaping/`?` substitution.\n107: - For the **`c`** style: wrap in double quotes and escape `\"` and `\\`, map\n108:   `\\t \\n \\r` etc. to their backslash forms, and emit remaining non-printables\n109:   as 3-digit octal `\\NNN`.\n110: - For **`shell`**: a name needs quoting if it is empty or contains any of the\n111:   shell-special characters (space, `'\"\\$\\`&|;<>()*?[]#~=%!{}` and control\n112:   chars); single-quote it, and for embedded single quotes use the\n113:   `'\\''` splice.\n114: - Map the short flags onto styles: `-N`→literal, `-Q`→c, `-b`→escape; the last\n115:   quoting-related flag on the command line wins, mirroring GNU precedence.\n\n(End of file - total 115 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Rust `ls` — Quoting & Escaping\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n**name quoting and escaping**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary\nlocated at `/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses entirely on **how filenames\ncontaining spaces, quotes, tabs, newlines, backslashes, and control characters\nare rendered** — long format, sorting, columns, color, and recursion are not the\nfocus here (entries are still name-sorted).\n\n## Required Flags\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-quoting/instruction.md","text":"# Rust `ls` — Quoting & Escaping\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that reproduces GNU coreutils `ls`\n**name quoting and escaping**. Your implementation must be a standalone binary\nlocated at `/app/workspace/rls`. It will be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses entirely on **how filenames\ncontaining spaces, quotes, tabs, newlines, backslashes, and control characters\nare rendered** — long format, sorting, columns, color, and recursion are not the\nfocus here (entries are still name-sorted).\n\n## Required Flags\n\nYou must support the following flags. Behavior must match GNU coreutils `ls`\nexactly.\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `-b`, `--escape` | Print C-style escapes (`\\t`, `\\n`, `\\\\`, `\\NNN`, …) for non-graphic chars |\n| `-q`, `--hide-control-chars` | Print `?` for each non-graphic char |\n| `-Q`, `--quote-name` | Enclose names in double quotes |\n| `-N`, `--literal` | Print raw names with no quoting or escaping |\n| `--show-control-chars` | Show non-graphic chars as-is (the opposite of `-q`) |\n| `--quoting-style=WORD` | `literal` / `shell` / `shell-always` / `shell-escape` / `shell-escape-always` / `c` / `escape` |\n\n### Combined in some cases\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `-l` | Long listing (cases that use it require correct long output) |\n\n## Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Usage |\n|----------|-------|\n| `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order and which bytes count as printable |\n| `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n| `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n\n## Output Behavior\n\nThe default quoting style for GNU `ls` is **`shell-escape`** when output is not\na terminal in recent coreutils — however, the test environment pins behavior via\nflags, so implement each named style precisely:\n\n- **`literal`** (`-N`): emit the raw bytes, no quoting.\n- **`shell`**: quote with single quotes only when needed (spaces, shell\n  metacharacters); otherwise bare.\n- **`shell-always`**: always single-quote.\n- **`shell-escape`** / **`shell-escape-always`**: like shell/shell-always but\n  use `$'…'` ANSI-C quoting for names containing control characters.\n- **`c`** (also `-Q`): double-quote the name and apply C escapes (`\\t`, `\\n`,\n  `\\\"`, `\\\\`, octal `\\NNN`).\n- **`escape`** (`-b`): C-style escapes **without** the surrounding quotes.\n- **`-q`** replaces every non-graphic character with `?` (independent of style).\n- **`--show-control-chars`** turns off the `-q` default substitution.\n\nWhen several of these are combined, GNU `ls` applies a defined precedence —\nreproduce it so the exact byte output matches.\n\n- **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n\n## Evaluation\n\nYour implementation is evaluated against a hidden suite built on a fixture of\nfilenames containing spaces, single/double quotes, tabs, backslashes, embedded\ncontrol characters, and a newline, plus a few ordinary fixtures. Each case runs\nyour binary and GNU `ls` on the same inputs, flags, and environment, and\ncompares output after trailing-whitespace normalization on each line; they must\nmatch exactly.\n\n## Time Limit\n\nYou have **2 hours** (7200 seconds). Implement `literal` first, then the `c`/\n`escape` styles, then the `shell*` family, then the `-q` substitution. When ~10\nminutes remain, run a final `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to\n`/app/workspace/rls`, and make sure it runs without crashing.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- You must implement this in **Rust**.\n- You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n  ready-made `ls` implementation.\n- You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n  `nix`, `clap`).\n- Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n- The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n- Each test has a per-case timeout (10 seconds).\n\n## Getting Started\n\nExample fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n`/app/fixtures/` and test definitions in `/app/tests/`.\n\n## Tips\n\n- Work at the **byte** level, not UTF-8 — filenames are arbitrary byte strings,\n  and under `LC_ALL=C` any byte outside the printable ASCII range (0x20–0x7E)\n  is \"non-graphic\" and subject to escaping/`?` substitution.\n- For the **`c`** style: wrap in double quotes and escape `\"` and `\\`, map\n  `\\t \\n \\r` etc. to their backslash forms, and emit remaining non-printables\n  as 3-digit octal `\\NNN`.\n- For **`shell`**: a name needs quoting if it is empty or contains any of the\n  shell-special characters (space, `'\"\\$\\`&|;<>()*?[]#~=%!{}` and control\n  chars); single-quote it, and for embedded single quotes use the\n  `'\\''` splice.\n- Map the short flags onto styles: `-N`→literal, `-Q`→c, `-b`→escape; the last\n  quoting-related flag on the command line wins, mirroring GNU precedence.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":115,"totalLines":115,"truncated":false}},"title":"rust-ls-quoting/instruction.md","time":{"start":1781082370195,"end":1781082370247}},"metadata":{"anthropic":{"caller":{"type":"direct"}}},"id":"prt_eb0c82f78001gxnW7ebefbih4s","sessionID":"ses_14f38057bffeIT5v3QDi2oCNBE","messageID":"msg_eb0c8252b001AJhQ7JigCzeIel"}}
